\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
The Maximum Circular Velocity Dependence of Halo Clustering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
The halo model provides a connection between dark matter halos and galaxies,
 and it has been remarkably successful in describing observations of galaxy
 clustering.
 In particular,
\color inherit
 the Halo Occupation Distribution (HOD) and the Conditional Luminosity Function
 (CLF) are the two most widely used models of the galaxy-halo connection.
 In order to populate halos with galaxies, the HOD gives the probability
 
\begin_inset Formula $P(N|M)$
\end_inset

 that a halo with mass 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{M}$
\end_inset

 hosts 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 galaxies, while the CLF models the mean abundance 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi(L|M)$
\end_inset

 of galaxies with luminosity 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 which live in a dark matter halo of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Those two models are convertible that we can obtain an HOD by integrating
 the CLF against luminosity and a CLF by differentiating the HOD with respect
 to luminosity.
 The fundamental assumption in both formalisms is that galaxy occupation
 statistics are characterized entirely by halo mass.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some studies show that the most important halo property that influences
 the properties of galaxies within halos is halo mass [White and Rees, 1978
 and one more].
 This is often extended to halo abundance and halo clustering as an assumption
 that halo mass is the most influential halo property to characterize its
 abundance and clustering.
 The motivation behind this assumption comes from the simple excursion set
 formalism, which models halo assembly and clustering from the random walks
 of the density fluctuation, with the assumption that halo environment and
 halo assembly history have no correlation.
 It, however, is shown that the excursion set theory predicts halo clustering
 depends on additional halo environmental factors by relaxing its assumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, the halo clustering in N-body simulations exhibits dependence
 on halo mass as well as on additional properties such as halo formation
 time [XXX].
 The dependence of halo clustering upon other properties besides halo mass
 is known as halo assembly bias.
 
\color black
There have been several studies showing the correlation between halo formation
 time and environment, and therefore any other properties that depend on
 formation time or environment (such as concentration, spin, and velocity
 anisotropy) affect to the assembly bias.
 If the galaxy properties in halos are affected by halo environment, it
 implies that the galaxy occupation statistics also correlate with halo
 assembly bias.
 Several groups study the correlation between galaxy formation and halo
 assembly bias both theoretically (Croton et al.
 2007) and observationally (XXX).
 Even though 
\color red
Ref.
 XXX[Croton et al.
 2007]
\color black
 shows the significant influence of halo assembly bias on galaxy clustering,
 there have been mixed responses to the detection of such a correlation
 observationally.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a response to halo assembly bias, a recent trend in connecting halos
 and galaxies has been to use the Abundance Matching technique.
 In the Abundance Matching technique, a monotonic relation between galaxy
 luminosity and the maximum circular velocities of halos is assumed so that
 one can assign the most luminous galaxy to the halo which have the largest
 maximum circular velocity and repeat the same procedure in a hierarchical
 manner.
 The motivation behind the technique is that the maximum circular velocity,
 which is a measure of the halos' potential well depth, correlates strongly
 with stellar mass of the galaxies and also generically predicts assembly
 bias.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper, we explore the additional dependence of galaxy clustering
 on the central velocity dispersion both on small and large scales.
 In Section 2, we briefly describe the simulations, halo finding algorithm,
 and identification of halo types.
 In Section 3, we compare halo clustering for samples which we select halos
 so that we can purely account for the maximum circular dependence of halo
 clustering.
 We also investigate the effect of ejected halos on the halo clustering.
 The ejected halos are the halos which were within the virial radius of
 more massive host halos in the past but identified as a distinguished halo
 at present epoch.
 There have been several studies discussing the possibilities that those
 ejected halos are not host halos but subhalos [
\color red
XXX: Wetzel et al.
 14, and some other references for backsplash radius...are there any better
 ways to phrase and also connect this to backsplash radius?
\color inherit
].
 So, it is crucial to explore how distnction of halo types affect to halo
 clustering.
 In Section4, we explore how the Abundance Matching techniques based on
 halo mass and the maximum circular velocity make qualitatively different
 predictions for the clustering of central galaxies to connect our findings
 in Section 3 to observations.
 In Section 5, we discuss the implications of our results and summarize
 our main conlusions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Simulation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use cosmological N-body simulations called the Bolshoi simulation [XXX:http:/
/arxiv.org/abs/1002.3660 (Klypin, Trujillo-Gomez, and Primack, 2011)] and
 the MultiDark simulation [XXX: http://arxiv.org/abs/1109.0003 (Riebe et al.,
 2012), Prada et al.
 2011] to investigate the maximum circular velocity dependence of halo clusterin
g.
 We use both simulations in order to obtain a large dynamic mass range.
 Both simulations assume a flat 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda{\rm CDM}$
\end_inset

 model with density parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{m}=0.27$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{\Lambda}=0.73$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{b}=0.0469$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{8}=0.82$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0.95$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $h=0.70$
\end_inset

.
 The Bolshoi simulation uses 
\begin_inset Formula $2048^{3}$
\end_inset

 particles in a periodic box with side length 
\begin_inset Formula $250h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

.
 The mass of each particle is 
\begin_inset Formula $1.35\times10^{8}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 with the force resolution 
\begin_inset Formula $1h^{-1}{\rm kpc}$
\end_inset

.
 The MultiDark simulation uses 
\begin_inset Formula $2048^{3}$
\end_inset

 particles in a periodic box with side length 
\begin_inset Formula $1000h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

.
 The mass of each particle is 
\begin_inset Formula $8.721\times10^{9}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 with the force resolution 
\begin_inset Formula $7h^{-1}{\rm kpc}$
\end_inset

.
 The simulations were run with the Adaptive Refinement Tree Code [ART: Kravtsov
 et al.
 1997, Gottloeber & Klypin 2008].
 Halo catalogues and snapshots for dark matter particles are available at
 
\begin_inset Flex URL
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

http://www.multidark.org
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use halo catalogues generated by the ROCKSTAR, which is a phase-space,
 temporal halo finder [XXX].
 The ROCKSTAR identifies halos and subhalos down to the maximum circular
 velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}\thicksim55{\rm km/s}$
\end_inset

 and also provides merger trees.
 Those catalogues are publicly available at 
\begin_inset Flex URL
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

http://hipacc.ucsc.edu/Bolshoi/MergerTrees.html
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on the halo catalogue, we classify halos into three different categories:
 host halo, subhalos, and ejected halos.
 Host halos are the halos that have never been within the virial radius
 of more massive halos.
 Subhalos are the halos which are within the virial radius of more massive
 halos at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
 Ejected halos, sometimes called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

backsplash
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 halos, are the distinct halos at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 whose main progenitors passed through the virial radius of a more massive
 halos at least once in the past.
 In order to identify ejected halos, we build a merger tree by using a merger
 tree algorithm CONSISTENT TREES[cite].
 In later sections, when we say halos without any specifications, we include
 both host halos and ejected halos.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dark matter halos in the halo catalogue at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 are defined to be spherical regions whose average density equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{{\rm h}}\rho_{{\rm crit}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{{\rm h}}=360$
\end_inset


\color black
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 according to Bryan & Norman fitting function for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda{\rm CDM}$
\end_inset

 cosmology [XXX] and whose radius 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}=4\pi\Omega_{m}\rho_{{\rm crit}}\Delta_{{\rm h}}R_{{\rm vir}}^{3}/3$
\end_inset

.
 Note that even though subhalos are distinct and bound objects within the
 host halos, the masses and radii of subhalos do not follow the above virial
 definition, because their structures are strongly affected by the potentials
 of their host halos.
 In order to define the maximum circular velocity for each halo, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{{\rm G}M(r)/r}$
\end_inset

 within the radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is repeatedly computed with increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $r<R_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

 until finding the maximum value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the sake of the internal structure of halos to be resolved well enough,
 we made a conservative cut in mass and maximum circular velocity.
 We use halos whose mass is greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{12}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 (corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $>100$
\end_inset

 particles per halo) and whose maximum circular velocity is greater than
 
\begin_inset Formula $200{\rm km/s}$
\end_inset

 for the MultiDark simulation, and halos whose mass is greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{11}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 (corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $>740$
\end_inset

 particles per halo) and whose maximum circular velocity is greater than
 
\begin_inset Formula $95{\rm km/s}$
\end_inset

 for the Bolshoi simulation.
 
\color red
Those values correspond to the peak in the number of halos by binning them
 as a function of mass and maximum circular velocity.
 
\color inherit
The halo samples below the halo mass or maximum circular velocoty corresponding
 to the peak are not considered to be complete based on the predictions
 for halo mass functions, which are a monotonically increasing function
 with the decrease in halo mass.
 As we will see in Section 3, simultaneous dependence of halo clustering
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

, the cut is not enough.
 But all the results pass this cut unless it is noted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Maximum Circular Velocity Dependence of Halo Clustering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we investigate the maximum circular velocity dependence
 of halo clustering on both large and small scales.
 We first start with an analytic expression of the maximum circular velocity
 computed from the halo mass and its concentration.
 Then, we explain how we select halos for each sample to remove the halo
 mass dependence using the analytic expression of the maximum circular velocity.
 Finally, we show how halo biases differ for those samples both on large
 scales and small scales.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Maximum Circular Velocity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to compute the maximum circular velocity for halos, we assume that
 dark matter halos are defined as a spherical halo with a virial radius.
 Those halos have average density equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{{\rm h}}\rho_{{\rm crit}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{{\rm h}}=360$
\end_inset

 
\color red
for 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 according to Bryan & Norman fitting function [XXX]
\color inherit
.
 We also assume that those spherical halos have an NFW density profile (XXX).
 Then, the maximum circular velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{V}_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 as a function of the halo mass 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

 and its concentration 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{V}_{{\rm max}}=0.465M_{{\rm vir}}^{1/3}\sqrt{G(\frac{4}{3}\pi\Delta_{{\rm h}}\rho_{{\rm crit}}\Omega_{m})^{1/3}\frac{c}{{\rm ln(1+c)-c/(1+c)}}}.\label{eq:vmax-mvir}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The median concentration-mass relation at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 obtained from the Bolshoi simulation in Ref.
 XXX(Klypin et al.
 2011) is: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
{\rm log}_{10}c=-0.097{\rm log_{10}M_{vir}}+2.148.\label{eq:concen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\color black
By using the above median concentration to Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:vmax-mvir"

\end_inset

, we obtain a one to one mapping between the virial halo mass and its maximum
 circular velocity, denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{V}_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 hereafter.

\color inherit
 Given this mapping, we can translate clustering measurements as a function
 of halo mass into predicted clustering measurements as a function of maximum
 circular velocity.
 Our goal below is to determine whether this conversion describes the measured
 clustering or if there is a residual dependence on the maximum circular
 velocity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Samples
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
