\end_inset

Distribution of halo mass and maximum circular velocity at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.0$
\end_inset

 for halos
\color black
 from the Bolshoi simulation.

\color inherit
 The blue dots represent halos whose observed maximum circular velocity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,obs}}$
\end_inset

, is greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{V}_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

, while the green dots are the ones with smaller 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,obs}}$
\end_inset

 than 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{V}_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

.
 The boundary between blue and green dots correspond to 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{V}_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 computed from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:vmax-mvir"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color red
To begin with, we split the sample of halos described in Section 2 into
 a sequence of virial mass bins from high mass to low mass, chosen such
 that there are the same numbers of halos in each bin.
 We select 200000 halos for each bin for the halo sample from the MultiDark
 simulation and 25000 halos for the Bolshoi simulation.
 
\color inherit
This process is reminiscent of an abundance matching procedure (cite XXX).
 We then further split each bin into two subsamples with their observed
 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,obs}}$
\end_inset

 greater than (denoted by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

upper
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) or less than (denoted as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lower
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{V}_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

.
 Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:vmax-mvir"

\end_inset

 shows the distribution of halo mass and maximum circular velocity classified
 into 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

upper
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (blue dots) and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lower
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (green dots) samples as an example.
 Note that the number of halos in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

upper
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lower
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 subsamples
\color black
 are 
\color inherit
almost equal for any halo mass bins.
 This selection ensures that both the upper and lower subsamples have the
 same mean halo mass.
 Therefore, in the absence of an additional 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 dependence on clustering, these samples should have the same clustering
 properties.

\color red
 Note that this would not be true if we had simply split the sample along
 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

, since the two resulting subsamples would have different mean halo masses.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Halo Bias
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to measure halo biases, we first compute halo-matter cross correlation
 functions for each subsample.
 We used cross correlation functions to reduce the shot noise effect on
 the error.
 Here, instead of using full DM particles, we subsample 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{6}$
\end_inset

 particles to compute the cross correlation functions and matter auto correlatio
n functions.
 Then, we define a linear bias: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
b_{{\rm lin}}=\sum_{i}(\xi_{hm}(r_{i})/\xi_{mm}(r_{i}))/N_{{\rm bin}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{hm}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{mm}$
\end_inset

 are halo-matter and matter-matter correlation functions and we take the
 average of the ratio on 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $10h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $20h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

, which contains 20 bins in total.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:linear-bias"

\end_inset

 shows linear biases as a function of halo mass by splitting each sample
 into 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

upper
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lower
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 subsamples.
 For large halo masses, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lower
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 subsamples have larger linear biases than the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

upper
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 subsamples.
 This result is consistent with the result discussed in Ref.
 XXX(Dalal et al.
 2008).
 For low halo masses, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

upper
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 subsamples have larger linear biases than the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lower
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 subsamples.
 Those halos, which have larger maximum circular velocities than 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{V}_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

, are the ones which are supposed to grow into larger mass halos, but somehow
 the mass growth is suppressed due to a tidal field [XXX: Wang et al.
 + Wetzel et al.
 2014].
 This is why those halos in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

upper
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 subsamples cluster more strongly than the ones in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lower
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 subsamples.
 As halo mass decreases, the difference in linear bias between the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

upper
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lower
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 subsamples increases up to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim40\%$
\end_inset

.
 On the low mass end, there is a drop in the ratio of the linear biases.
 As we see no physical reasons, consider that this is a resolution effect
 and suggest that the condition required for completeness is more stringent
 [XXX: Peter's paper].
\end_layout

